1
00:00:51,152 --> 00:00:53,705
Baltimore, Maryland 1980

2
00:01:58,960 --> 00:02:01,993
<i>Think to yourself
that every day is your last...</i>

3
00:02:02,256 --> 00:02:04,166
<i>the hour to which
you do not look forward...</i>

4
00:02:04,239 --> 00:02:06,247
<i>will come as a welcome surprise.</i>

5
00:02:06,448 --> 00:02:07,822
<i>As for me...</i>

6
00:02:07,888 --> 00:02:09,262
<i>when you want a good laugh...</i>

7
00:02:09,328 --> 00:02:11,816
<i>you will find me, in a fine state...</i>

8
00:02:12,048 --> 00:02:13,673
<i>fat and sleek...</i>

9
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:16,942
<i>a true hog of Epicurus' herd.</i>

10
00:02:19,184 --> 00:02:22,632
And we find you cribbing lines
from Horace, as well.

11
00:02:23,664 --> 00:02:25,038
Well done, John.

12
00:02:25,136 --> 00:02:26,761
I must say, Hannibal...

13
00:02:26,864 --> 00:02:28,774
speaking for the rest of the herd...

14
00:02:29,936 --> 00:02:32,391
I'm sorry, for the Symphony Board...

15
00:02:32,943 --> 00:02:34,732
that these little soirees of yours...

16
00:02:34,800 --> 00:02:37,037
are always the highlight of our year.

17
00:02:37,168 --> 00:02:39,590
- Just so.
- You're too kind.

18
00:02:39,888 --> 00:02:44,525
I do feel guilty enjoying
tonight when a musician is...

19
00:02:44,624 --> 00:02:46,533
still listed as a missing person.

20
00:02:46,608 --> 00:02:48,233
Yes, poor fellow.

21
00:02:49,200 --> 00:02:51,175
Shall I confess something wicked?

22
00:02:51,279 --> 00:02:56,135
I can't help feeling
the tiniest bit... relieved.

23
00:02:57,647 --> 00:02:59,208
It sounds awful, I know.

24
00:02:59,280 --> 00:03:02,149
But, let's face it,
so does the man's playing.

25
00:03:02,799 --> 00:03:04,490
Hannibal, confess.

26
00:03:04,944 --> 00:03:07,911
What is this divine-looking
amuse-bouche?

27
00:03:08,848 --> 00:03:10,277
If I tell you...

28
00:03:11,760 --> 00:03:13,669
I'm afraid you won't even try it.

29
00:03:18,384 --> 00:03:20,391
- Bon appétit.
- Bon appétit.

30
00:03:36,368 --> 00:03:39,335
Special Agent Graham.
What an unexpected pleasure.

31
00:03:39,408 --> 00:03:42,441
I'm sorry to bother you again,
Dr. Lecter. I know it's late.

32
00:03:42,544 --> 00:03:45,577
It's no bother.
We're both night owls, I think.

33
00:03:45,936 --> 00:03:47,911
- Come in, please.
- Thank you.

34
00:03:48,015 --> 00:03:49,837
Let me take your coat.

35
00:03:50,703 --> 00:03:52,013
What's on your mind?

36
00:03:52,080 --> 00:03:55,854
We've been on the wrong track
this whole time. You and I.

37
00:03:55,984 --> 00:03:57,991
Our whole profile's wrong.

38
00:03:58,256 --> 00:04:00,841
We've been looking for someone
with a crazy grudge...

39
00:04:00,944 --> 00:04:02,951
and some kind of anatomical knowledge.

40
00:04:03,056 --> 00:04:05,958
Decertified doctors,
med school dropouts...

41
00:04:06,063 --> 00:04:07,209
laid-off mortuary workers...

42
00:04:07,280 --> 00:04:11,109
From the precision of the cuts,
and his choice of souvenirs.

43
00:04:11,215 --> 00:04:12,644
That's where we're off-target.

44
00:04:12,720 --> 00:04:14,859
He's not collecting body parts.

45
00:04:14,960 --> 00:04:18,854
- Then why keep them?
- He's not. He's eating them.

46
00:04:20,496 --> 00:04:23,114
No, listen. We were at
Molly's parents' for New Year's...

47
00:04:23,216 --> 00:04:25,038
and her dad was showing
my son, Josh...

48
00:04:25,136 --> 00:04:26,958
how to carve a roasted chicken.

49
00:04:27,056 --> 00:04:29,838
He said, "The tenderest part
of the chicken is the oysters...

50
00:04:29,936 --> 00:04:31,725
"on either side of the back."

51
00:04:32,624 --> 00:04:35,919
I had never heard that
expression before, "oysters."

52
00:04:36,623 --> 00:04:40,071
Then suddenly I had a flash
of the third victim...

53
00:04:40,176 --> 00:04:41,419
Darcy Taylor.

54
00:04:41,935 --> 00:04:45,132
She was missing flesh from
her back. And then it hit me.

55
00:04:45,232 --> 00:04:48,265
Liver, kidney, tongue, thymus.

56
00:04:48,336 --> 00:04:51,849
Every single victim lost
some body part used in cooking.

57
00:04:52,687 --> 00:04:55,142
Have you shared this with the Bureau?

58
00:04:55,215 --> 00:04:58,696
No, I needed to see you first.
But I'm right. I know I'm right.

59
00:04:58,768 --> 00:05:01,102
I'm starting to be able to think
like this one.

60
00:05:01,168 --> 00:05:02,859
Yeah, it's fascinating.

61
00:05:03,792 --> 00:05:07,404
You know, I'd always suspected
as much. You are an eidetiker.

62
00:05:08,176 --> 00:05:09,605
I'm not psychic, Doctor.

63
00:05:09,712 --> 00:05:11,567
No, this is different.

64
00:05:11,856 --> 00:05:13,798
More akin to artistic imagination.

65
00:05:14,608 --> 00:05:17,455
You can assume the emotional
point of view of others...

66
00:05:17,551 --> 00:05:19,973
even those that might scare
or sicken you.

67
00:05:20,175 --> 00:05:22,597
It's a troubling gift, I should think.

68
00:05:22,703 --> 00:05:25,224
How I'd love to get you on my couch.

69
00:05:26,352 --> 00:05:28,588
Something still doesn't
make sense to me.

70
00:05:28,688 --> 00:05:31,721
You're the best
forensic psychiatrist I know...

71
00:05:32,432 --> 00:05:34,341
and somehow,
in all our time together...

72
00:05:34,416 --> 00:05:36,326
this possibility
never occurred to you.

73
00:05:37,392 --> 00:05:40,741
I am only human, Will.
Perhaps I made a mistake.

74
00:05:40,943 --> 00:05:44,326
You don't strike me as a man
who makes very many mistakes.

75
00:05:44,464 --> 00:05:45,893
Now I'm sorry to think I might...

76
00:05:45,968 --> 00:05:48,139
no longer enjoy your full confidence.

77
00:05:49,231 --> 00:05:51,500
No, I didn't say that.

78
00:05:53,423 --> 00:05:55,562
I don't know what I'm saying.

79
00:05:56,016 --> 00:05:57,804
I'm very, very tired.

80
00:06:01,296 --> 00:06:02,889
I almost had it.

81
00:06:03,824 --> 00:06:05,482
It'll come to you.

82
00:06:06,032 --> 00:06:08,006
Why don't you come back
in the morning?

83
00:06:08,112 --> 00:06:10,251
I'll clear some time
on my schedule and...

84
00:06:10,351 --> 00:06:12,839
then we can get started
in revising our profile.

85
00:06:12,944 --> 00:06:14,537
- Sound good?
- Yeah.

86
00:06:14,608 --> 00:06:17,063
Rest here, and I'll get your coat.

87
00:06:18,256 --> 00:06:19,849
Won't be a tick.

88
00:07:18,352 --> 00:07:19,562
Don't move.

89
00:07:20,016 --> 00:07:23,399
You're in shock now. I don't
want you to feel any pain.

90
00:07:23,952 --> 00:07:27,530
In a moment you'll begin to be
light-headed. Then drowsy.

91
00:07:27,792 --> 00:07:31,785
Don't resist. It's so gentle.
Like slipping into a warm bath.

92
00:07:34,896 --> 00:07:36,903
I regret it came to this, Will.

93
00:07:36,976 --> 00:07:39,180
But every game must have its ending.

94
00:07:45,104 --> 00:07:46,630
Remarkable boy.

95
00:07:46,800 --> 00:07:48,775
I do admire your courage.

96
00:07:50,864 --> 00:07:53,035
I think I'll eat your heart.

97
00:10:46,831 --> 00:10:50,988
Marathon, Florida Several Years Later

98
00:11:06,704 --> 00:11:08,744
Hey, Dad. Someone's here.

99
00:11:13,744 --> 00:11:14,824
Hey.

100
00:11:16,687 --> 00:11:18,859
You've got
a beautiful setup here, Will.

101
00:11:18,960 --> 00:11:20,302
Yeah, it's good.

102
00:11:21,104 --> 00:11:24,846
- You know why I'm here?
- Yeah, I can guess.

103
00:11:25,968 --> 00:11:27,429
How much do you know?

104
00:11:27,503 --> 00:11:30,537
Just what was in
the Miami Herald and the Times.

105
00:11:31,024 --> 00:11:34,188
Two families killed
a month apart in their homes.

106
00:11:34,512 --> 00:11:38,124
Birmingham and Atlanta.
The circumstances were similar.

107
00:11:39,088 --> 00:11:40,910
Not similar. The same.

108
00:11:41,680 --> 00:11:43,720
What have you kept out of the papers?

109
00:11:43,792 --> 00:11:46,475
He smashes mirrors
and uses the pieces.

110
00:11:46,672 --> 00:11:50,283
Wears latex gloves, so we've got
no prints. Size 11 shoe.

111
00:11:51,888 --> 00:11:53,710
He's not too comfortable with locks.

112
00:11:53,840 --> 00:11:55,662
Pried open a patio door
in Birmingham...

113
00:11:55,760 --> 00:11:57,548
used a glass cutter in Atlanta.

114
00:11:58,512 --> 00:12:00,617
And his blood's AB positive.

115
00:12:01,232 --> 00:12:03,141
- Somebody hurt him?
- Nope.

116
00:12:04,112 --> 00:12:07,428
We typed him from semen
and saliva. He's a secretor.

117
00:12:11,888 --> 00:12:14,986
Tell me something, Will.
You knew what this was.

118
00:12:15,759 --> 00:12:18,759
Did you ever consider picking up
the phone and giving me a call?

119
00:12:18,832 --> 00:12:20,141
You've got all the people you need.

120
00:12:20,240 --> 00:12:23,950
You've got Dortmund at Harvard.
You got Bloom in Chicago.

121
00:12:24,047 --> 00:12:26,219
I've got you down here
fixing boat motors?

122
00:12:26,319 --> 00:12:28,621
Yeah, I like fixing boat motors.

123
00:12:29,647 --> 00:12:31,502
I wouldn't be very useful to you.

124
00:12:31,600 --> 00:12:32,942
I don't think about it anymore.

125
00:12:33,039 --> 00:12:35,592
Really?
The last two we had, you caught.

126
00:12:35,663 --> 00:12:38,216
By doing what you
and the other guys are doing.

127
00:12:38,320 --> 00:12:40,687
That's not entirely true.
It's the way you think.

128
00:12:40,752 --> 00:12:44,265
Come on. There's been a lot of
bullshit about the way I think.

129
00:12:44,368 --> 00:12:46,473
I've got technicians
to examine evidence...

130
00:12:46,544 --> 00:12:47,885
but you've got that other thing.

131
00:12:47,952 --> 00:12:51,115
Imagination. Projection.
Whatever.

132
00:12:51,344 --> 00:12:54,857
- I know you don't like it.
- You wouldn't like it, either.

133
00:13:16,272 --> 00:13:18,377
This freak killed the Jacobis
in Birmingham...

134
00:13:18,480 --> 00:13:20,901
on Saturday night, February 25.
Full moon.

135
00:13:21,008 --> 00:13:22,863
He killed the Leeds family
in Atlanta...

136
00:13:22,959 --> 00:13:24,137
a few nights ago, March 28.

137
00:13:24,240 --> 00:13:25,996
One day short of a lunar month.

138
00:13:26,064 --> 00:13:28,453
If we're lucky, we may have
a little over three weeks...

139
00:13:28,560 --> 00:13:30,186
before he does it again.

140
00:13:30,672 --> 00:13:32,876
Will, do you respect my judgment?

141
00:13:34,512 --> 00:13:35,624
Of course.

142
00:13:35,728 --> 00:13:39,111
I think we have a better chance
to catch him fast if you help.

143
00:13:39,248 --> 00:13:41,703
Go to Atlanta and look.
Just look.

144
00:13:42,384 --> 00:13:44,872
Then help me brief the locals.
That's it.

145
00:13:46,064 --> 00:13:47,973
Crawford has
the whole damn government.

146
00:13:48,080 --> 00:13:49,062
Why does he need you?

147
00:13:49,168 --> 00:13:51,950
He just wants me to look
at some evidence, Molly.

148
00:13:52,048 --> 00:13:54,219
Give him another point of view.

149
00:13:54,864 --> 00:13:57,897
It's a few days, a week maybe,
and I'll be right back.

150
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:00,139
- And you believed that?
- Yes.

151
00:14:01,680 --> 00:14:04,200
These kinds of cases
come up very rarely...

152
00:14:04,272 --> 00:14:05,581
and I've had experience.

153
00:14:05,680 --> 00:14:07,141
Yes, you have.

154
00:14:08,848 --> 00:14:10,636
You're paid up, Will.

155
00:14:11,120 --> 00:14:13,673
All of us. Even Josh.

156
00:14:15,280 --> 00:14:18,793
There's a chance I could
help them save some lives.

157
00:14:19,343 --> 00:14:21,318
How do I say no to that?

158
00:14:29,199 --> 00:14:32,199
This one will never see me
or know my name.

159
00:14:33,999 --> 00:14:35,887
I'll just help them find him.

160
00:14:35,952 --> 00:14:37,708
The cops will take him down, not me.

161
00:14:43,120 --> 00:14:45,738
I'll be in the back of the pack,
Molly, I promise.

162
00:14:45,840 --> 00:14:47,563
Never in your life.

163
00:14:50,704 --> 00:14:54,348
- I know you.
- Come on. Come here.

164
00:14:58,959 --> 00:15:00,301
I love you.

165
00:15:00,400 --> 00:15:02,123
- See you in a few days.
- Okay.

166
00:15:02,992 --> 00:15:04,748
I'll call you tonight.

167
00:15:15,183 --> 00:15:16,460
Bye, Dad!

168
00:15:27,472 --> 00:15:30,701
Leeds House, Atlanta, Georgia

169
00:15:49,808 --> 00:15:52,677
Where's the dog?
No one heard barking.

170
00:15:53,167 --> 00:15:55,818
There's nothing about it
in the case file.

171
00:17:58,864 --> 00:18:02,825
The intruder enters in the dark
and cuts Charles Leeds' throat.

172
00:18:03,120 --> 00:18:05,968
He shoots Valerie Leeds in
the stomach as she's rising...

173
00:18:06,032 --> 00:18:08,366
disabling her but not killing her.

174
00:18:09,999 --> 00:18:12,301
He leaves her
to watch her husband die...

175
00:18:12,720 --> 00:18:15,142
then turns and goes down the hall.

176
00:18:39,312 --> 00:18:41,166
The children were....

177
00:18:44,528 --> 00:18:47,081
The children were still in bed
when they were shot...

178
00:18:47,152 --> 00:18:50,119
which might indicate
that he used a silencer.

179
00:18:57,840 --> 00:19:01,418
He dragged the bodies into
the master bedroom, but why?

180
00:19:02,128 --> 00:19:05,543
They were already dead
and none of them got the same...

181
00:19:06,448 --> 00:19:09,033
extra attention as Mrs. Leeds.

182
00:19:38,160 --> 00:19:40,070
Small pieces of mirror
were inserted...

183
00:19:40,143 --> 00:19:42,696
in the orbital sockets of the victims.

184
00:19:43,088 --> 00:19:45,095
This occurred post-mortem.

185
00:19:54,480 --> 00:19:56,749
Why did you put mirrors in their eyes?

186
00:21:06,287 --> 00:21:09,484
The pieces of mirror are to make
their eyes look alive!

187
00:21:09,552 --> 00:21:13,065
He wanted an audience.
He wanted them all lined up...

188
00:21:13,168 --> 00:21:15,557
watching him when he touched her.

189
00:21:17,392 --> 00:21:19,181
When he touched her.

190
00:21:22,768 --> 00:21:25,899
Touched. Talcum powder.

191
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:27,942
There was talcum powder.

192
00:21:31,440 --> 00:21:34,288
"Mrs. Leeds had traces of
talcum on her right inner thigh.

193
00:21:34,352 --> 00:21:35,596
"A complete search of the home...

194
00:21:35,664 --> 00:21:38,347
"led to no such matching talcum
in the house."

195
00:21:40,464 --> 00:21:43,660
You took your gloves off,
didn't you? You son of a bitch!

196
00:21:44,560 --> 00:21:46,535
You took your gloves off, touched her...

197
00:21:46,640 --> 00:21:48,266
with your bare hand
and wiped her down.

198
00:21:48,367 --> 00:21:50,953
But when the gloves were off,
did you open her eyes?

199
00:21:59,087 --> 00:22:00,036
Crawford.

200
00:22:00,112 --> 00:22:02,184
Are the Leeds' bodies
still at the morgue?

201
00:22:02,864 --> 00:22:05,166
Who's good with latent prints here?

202
00:22:05,232 --> 00:22:06,180
Atlanta P.D.

203
00:22:06,288 --> 00:22:07,881
They've already printed the bodies.

204
00:22:07,952 --> 00:22:10,156
Not the bodies.
Tell them to check the eyes.

205
00:22:10,288 --> 00:22:12,743
Mrs. Leeds' eyes.
Even her corneas.

206
00:22:13,104 --> 00:22:16,846
I think he took his gloves off.
I think he had to touch her.

207
00:22:17,583 --> 00:22:18,990
Jesus, Will.

208
00:22:20,559 --> 00:22:22,054
Gentlemen. Ladies.

209
00:22:22,223 --> 00:22:24,427
This is what the subject's teeth
look like.

210
00:22:24,528 --> 00:22:27,724
The impressions came from
bite marks on Mrs. Leeds.

211
00:22:28,591 --> 00:22:30,795
This degree of crookedness...

212
00:22:31,248 --> 00:22:33,899
plus the groove
in this central incisor...

213
00:22:34,192 --> 00:22:35,948
makes his bite signature unique.

214
00:22:36,112 --> 00:22:37,421
Fuckin' shark.

215
00:22:38,480 --> 00:22:39,909
Knock it off!

216
00:22:41,232 --> 00:22:43,086
We're grateful to have the FBI.

217
00:22:43,152 --> 00:22:44,842
They have a lot of expertise
in this area.

218
00:22:44,911 --> 00:22:46,919
In particular,
Investigator Graham does.

219
00:22:46,992 --> 00:22:48,268
That right, Jack?

220
00:22:48,368 --> 00:22:49,644
Yes, sir.

221
00:22:50,032 --> 00:22:52,453
Anything you want to add,
Mr. Graham?

222
00:22:52,720 --> 00:22:55,469
Why don't you come
on up to the front, please?

223
00:22:57,328 --> 00:22:59,117
- That's the guy.
- Was he?

224
00:22:59,248 --> 00:23:01,550
Yeah, that's the guy
who arrested Lecter.

225
00:23:01,648 --> 00:23:03,142
I thought he retired.

226
00:23:03,247 --> 00:23:06,029
The son of a bitch
just about gutted him.

227
00:23:11,087 --> 00:23:14,383
Mrs. Leeds and Mrs. Jacobi
were the primary targets.

228
00:23:14,544 --> 00:23:17,805
The others were killed
just to complete his fantasy.

229
00:23:17,903 --> 00:23:21,002
I know that might be hard
to accept given what you saw...

230
00:23:21,072 --> 00:23:23,014
but this was not random.

231
00:23:23,120 --> 00:23:26,916
This wasn't some killing frenzy.
He was never out of control.

232
00:23:27,632 --> 00:23:30,981
These attacks were organized,
the women carefully chosen.

233
00:23:31,087 --> 00:23:33,575
We don't know
how he's choosing them, or why.

234
00:23:33,680 --> 00:23:36,265
They lived in different states
and never met.

235
00:23:36,368 --> 00:23:37,961
But there is some connection.

236
00:23:38,288 --> 00:23:41,321
There's some common factor,
and that's the key.

237
00:23:41,712 --> 00:23:44,362
Find out what that is,
and we'll save lives.

238
00:23:44,431 --> 00:23:47,628
'Cause this one
is gonna go on and on...

239
00:23:47,792 --> 00:23:50,377
until we get smart or we get lucky.

240
00:23:51,952 --> 00:23:53,414
He won't stop.

241
00:23:54,608 --> 00:23:57,575
- Why not?
- Because it makes him God.

242
00:23:59,024 --> 00:24:00,934
Would you give that up?

243
00:24:02,512 --> 00:24:06,124
You asked about the dog.
Last night a vet called us.

244
00:24:06,320 --> 00:24:08,873
Leeds and his oldest boy
brought the dog in...

245
00:24:08,943 --> 00:24:10,602
the afternoon before they were killed.

246
00:24:10,832 --> 00:24:13,036
Had a puncture wound to its abdomen.

247
00:24:13,104 --> 00:24:14,795
The vet had to put it down.

248
00:24:14,864 --> 00:24:17,100
Was it wearing a collar
with the address on it?

249
00:24:17,200 --> 00:24:18,215
No.

250
00:24:19,343 --> 00:24:22,158
- Did the Jacobis have a dog?
- No dog.

251
00:24:22,223 --> 00:24:24,111
They found a litter box
in the basement...

252
00:24:24,208 --> 00:24:26,477
cat droppings in it, no cat.

253
00:24:28,304 --> 00:24:31,784
If the cat was attacked,
the Jacobis may have buried it.

254
00:24:32,783 --> 00:24:35,401
Ask Birmingham to check that backyard.

255
00:24:35,472 --> 00:24:37,675
And tell them to use
a methane probe, it's faster.

256
00:24:41,264 --> 00:24:44,777
Yeah. It's for you.

257
00:24:46,672 --> 00:24:47,949
Crawford.

258
00:24:51,664 --> 00:24:53,900
Carl, you're the light of my life.

259
00:24:54,128 --> 00:24:55,589
Would it hold up in court?

260
00:24:55,823 --> 00:24:57,514
Okay. Great work.

261
00:24:59,152 --> 00:25:02,829
They found a print on
Mrs. Leeds' eye. Partial thumb.

262
00:25:04,240 --> 00:25:06,607
Besides that,
there's nothing else to tell you.

263
00:25:06,672 --> 00:25:07,654
Thank you for your time.

264
00:25:07,760 --> 00:25:09,353
I can't answer more questions.

265
00:25:09,423 --> 00:25:11,463
Will Graham! Remember me?

266
00:25:12,240 --> 00:25:16,037
Freddy Lounds. I covered
the Lecter case for the Tattler.

267
00:25:16,239 --> 00:25:18,127
- Did the paperback.
- Yeah, I remember.

268
00:25:18,192 --> 00:25:20,396
When did they bring you in?
What've you got?

269
00:25:20,848 --> 00:25:24,109
You think the Tooth Fairy
will be bigger than Lecter?

270
00:25:24,208 --> 00:25:26,445
I mean, he's already beaten
Lecter's score...

271
00:25:26,608 --> 00:25:29,477
You write lying shit,
and the Tattler is an asswipe!

272
00:25:29,552 --> 00:25:31,407
You stay away from me.

273
00:25:31,728 --> 00:25:33,353
Get away, Lounds.

274
00:25:34,992 --> 00:25:36,901
How about an exclusive?

275
00:25:39,568 --> 00:25:41,161
Sorry about that.

276
00:25:41,264 --> 00:25:44,297
That guy snuck into the hospital
and took those pictures of me.

277
00:25:44,400 --> 00:25:46,472
Remember? With the tubes
hanging out of me?

278
00:25:46,544 --> 00:25:47,821
Forget that prick.

279
00:25:48,144 --> 00:25:49,573
Give yourself some credit.

280
00:25:49,648 --> 00:25:51,306
When we catch the Tooth Fairy...

281
00:25:51,407 --> 00:25:53,960
that print plus his teeth
will burn him.

282
00:25:54,383 --> 00:25:55,790
You did that, Will.

283
00:25:55,888 --> 00:25:57,830
That evidence was there, Jack.

284
00:25:58,320 --> 00:26:02,117
- It was there for anyone to see.
- But nobody else did.

285
00:26:02,192 --> 00:26:04,461
All I'm sayin' is,
that was very good work.

286
00:26:04,560 --> 00:26:07,178
No, good work would be seeing it
all the way through...

287
00:26:07,280 --> 00:26:08,686
and catching the guy.

288
00:26:08,752 --> 00:26:12,047
And I can't do that.
I did what you asked me to do.

289
00:26:12,623 --> 00:26:14,150
I'm going home.

290
00:26:15,503 --> 00:26:18,056
I don't even have any idea
who this guy is.

291
00:26:18,160 --> 00:26:21,422
What I just gave them was broad
strokes. He's got no face to me.

292
00:26:21,519 --> 00:26:24,302
That's what you said about
Garrett Hobbs, remember?

293
00:26:24,399 --> 00:26:26,855
- And you figured him out.
- No, I didn't.

294
00:26:26,960 --> 00:26:29,578
- You didn't?
- No, I was stuck on Hobbs.

295
00:26:31,504 --> 00:26:32,878
I had help.

296
00:26:37,200 --> 00:26:38,607
From Lecter.

297
00:26:40,944 --> 00:26:42,056
Yeah.

298
00:26:46,800 --> 00:26:49,866
Jack, don't play games with me.
Don't do it.

299
00:26:50,960 --> 00:26:52,683
Just tell me what's on your mind.

300
00:26:52,752 --> 00:26:56,047
I'm saying maybe we've got
a resource we should look into.

301
00:26:56,112 --> 00:26:57,541
Is that what this was about?

302
00:26:57,647 --> 00:26:59,589
Did you just want to ask me that
all along?

303
00:26:59,663 --> 00:27:01,835
Don't get mad at me.
I'm just doing my job.

304
00:27:01,904 --> 00:27:04,205
If you know a better shortcut,
let me know it.

305
00:27:04,272 --> 00:27:06,638
If you think there's any chance
he'll talk to me...

306
00:27:06,704 --> 00:27:08,264
I'll go myself.

307
00:27:09,712 --> 00:27:13,803
If you can't handle it,
God knows I'd understand that.

308
00:27:20,720 --> 00:27:24,517
As a research subject, Lecter
has proven most disappointing.

309
00:27:25,040 --> 00:27:28,236
He's simply impenetrable
to psychological testing.

310
00:27:28,528 --> 00:27:30,983
Rorschach, Thematic Apperception.

311
00:27:31,312 --> 00:27:33,199
He folds them into origami.

312
00:27:34,512 --> 00:27:35,886
As you see.

313
00:27:37,040 --> 00:27:39,244
So you can imagine the stir
your little visit...

314
00:27:39,312 --> 00:27:41,254
is causing among my staff,
Mr. Graham.

315
00:27:42,704 --> 00:27:44,875
If you'd care
to share some insights...

316
00:27:44,943 --> 00:27:48,042
Dr. Chilton, I'm sorry, I've got
a 4:17 flight back to Atlanta.

317
00:27:48,112 --> 00:27:49,421
Of course.

318
00:27:52,560 --> 00:27:55,178
Tell me,
when you saw Lecter's murders...

319
00:27:55,280 --> 00:27:56,840
their style, so to speak...

320
00:27:56,911 --> 00:28:00,228
were you able, perhaps,
to reconstruct his fantasies?

321
00:28:00,303 --> 00:28:03,151
And, if so, did you jot down
any impressions?

322
00:28:03,248 --> 00:28:04,262
No.

323
00:28:11,504 --> 00:28:13,228
Let me be frank, Mr. Graham.

324
00:28:13,327 --> 00:28:17,484
The first analysis of Lecter
will be a publisher's wet dream.

325
00:28:17,552 --> 00:28:20,072
I'd give you full credit, of course.

326
00:28:23,728 --> 00:28:27,111
Damn it, man. You must have
some advice. You caught him.

327
00:28:27,183 --> 00:28:28,744
What was your trick?

328
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:31,658
I let him kill me.

329
00:29:23,152 --> 00:29:26,600
That's the same atrocious
aftershave you wore in court.

330
00:29:28,432 --> 00:29:30,057
I keep getting it for Christmas.

331
00:29:30,160 --> 00:29:34,153
Christmas, yes.
Did you get my card?

332
00:29:35,504 --> 00:29:36,748
I got it, thank you.

333
00:29:36,847 --> 00:29:40,044
So nice of the Bureau's
crime lab to forward that.

334
00:29:41,103 --> 00:29:43,886
They wouldn't give me
your home address.

335
00:29:45,072 --> 00:29:47,658
Dr. Bloom sent me your article
on surgical addiction...

336
00:29:47,760 --> 00:29:50,127
in the Journal of Forensic Psychiatry.

337
00:29:50,191 --> 00:29:51,173
And?

338
00:29:52,048 --> 00:29:54,503
Very interesting, even to a layman.

339
00:29:59,408 --> 00:30:01,382
You say you're a layman.

340
00:30:08,400 --> 00:30:12,109
But it was you who caught me.
Wasn't it, Will?

341
00:30:13,872 --> 00:30:17,255
- Do you know how you did it?
- I got lucky.

342
00:30:18,127 --> 00:30:20,396
I don't think you believe that.

343
00:30:21,360 --> 00:30:23,662
It's in the transcript.
What does it matter now?

344
00:30:23,760 --> 00:30:25,996
It doesn't matter to me, Will.

345
00:30:26,128 --> 00:30:28,397
I need your advice, Dr. Lecter.

346
00:30:30,672 --> 00:30:32,843
Birmingham and Atlanta.

347
00:30:33,487 --> 00:30:36,586
You want to know how
he's choosing them, don't you?

348
00:30:36,720 --> 00:30:39,502
I thought you'd have ideas.
I want you to tell me them.

349
00:30:39,600 --> 00:30:40,877
Why should I?

350
00:30:40,944 --> 00:30:42,285
There are things you don't have.

351
00:30:42,352 --> 00:30:44,905
Research materials.
Maybe even computer access.

352
00:30:45,007 --> 00:30:46,501
I'd speak to the Chief of Staff.

353
00:30:46,800 --> 00:30:48,458
Yes, Dr. Chilton.

354
00:30:49,744 --> 00:30:51,402
Gruesome, isn't he?

355
00:30:51,472 --> 00:30:55,563
He fumbles at your head like
a freshman pulling at panties.

356
00:30:56,783 --> 00:30:58,344
If you recall, Will...

357
00:30:58,447 --> 00:31:00,782
our last collaboration
ended rather messily.

358
00:31:03,440 --> 00:31:05,993
You'd get to see the file
on this case.

359
00:31:06,224 --> 00:31:09,639
- And there's another reason.
- I'm all ears.

360
00:31:10,288 --> 00:31:12,589
I thought you might enjoy
the challenge.

361
00:31:12,720 --> 00:31:15,502
Find out if you're smarter
than the person I'm looking for.

362
00:31:22,544 --> 00:31:26,156
Then, by implication, you think
you're smarter than I am...

363
00:31:26,224 --> 00:31:28,296
since it was you who caught me.

364
00:31:28,432 --> 00:31:30,220
I know I'm not smarter than you.

365
00:31:30,320 --> 00:31:32,043
Then how did you catch me?

366
00:31:32,240 --> 00:31:34,662
You had disadvantages.

367
00:31:34,992 --> 00:31:36,715
What disadvantages?

368
00:31:37,200 --> 00:31:38,662
You're insane.

369
00:31:43,760 --> 00:31:45,800
You're very tanned, Will.

370
00:31:46,032 --> 00:31:49,480
And your hands are so rough.
Not like a cop's hands anymore.

371
00:31:49,552 --> 00:31:52,552
And that shaving lotion is
something a child would select.

372
00:31:52,623 --> 00:31:55,591
Has a little ship on the bottle,
does it not?

373
00:31:56,240 --> 00:31:59,087
And how is young Josh
and the lovely Molly?

374
00:31:59,887 --> 00:32:02,189
They're always in my thoughts,
you know.

375
00:32:02,288 --> 00:32:04,197
You will not persuade me
with appeals...

376
00:32:04,272 --> 00:32:05,679
to my intellectual vanity.

377
00:32:05,744 --> 00:32:07,500
I don't think
I'll persuade you at all.

378
00:32:07,600 --> 00:32:09,323
You'll either do it or you won't.

379
00:32:09,391 --> 00:32:11,563
- Is that the case file?
- Yes.

380
00:32:11,919 --> 00:32:13,064
With photos?

381
00:32:13,168 --> 00:32:15,241
Let me keep them,
and I might consider it.

382
00:32:15,407 --> 00:32:16,301
No.

383
00:32:19,472 --> 00:32:21,381
Do you dream much, Will?

384
00:32:21,488 --> 00:32:22,949
Goodbye, Dr. Lecter.

385
00:32:23,024 --> 00:32:26,188
You haven't threatened
to take away my books yet!

386
00:32:26,352 --> 00:32:28,261
Give me the file, then!

387
00:32:29,744 --> 00:32:32,046
And I'll tell you what I think.

388
00:32:34,544 --> 00:32:36,911
I'll need one hour. And privacy.

389
00:32:43,408 --> 00:32:45,644
Just like old times, Will?

390
00:33:14,352 --> 00:33:16,556
This is a very shy boy, Will.

391
00:33:17,072 --> 00:33:18,763
I'd love to meet him.

392
00:33:18,832 --> 00:33:21,799
Have you considered
that he is disfigured...

393
00:33:21,872 --> 00:33:23,912
or that he may believe
he is disfigured?

394
00:33:23,984 --> 00:33:25,478
Yeah, the mirrors.

395
00:33:25,552 --> 00:33:27,439
Notice he smashes all the mirrors...

396
00:33:27,503 --> 00:33:29,543
not just enough
to get the pieces he wants.

397
00:33:29,648 --> 00:33:31,819
And, of course,
those shards in their eyes...

398
00:33:31,920 --> 00:33:33,196
so he can see himself there.

399
00:33:33,328 --> 00:33:34,473
That's interesting.

400
00:33:34,544 --> 00:33:36,616
No, it's not.
You thought of it before.

401
00:33:37,232 --> 00:33:38,988
I had considered it.

402
00:33:39,120 --> 00:33:41,160
- What about the women?
- Dead?

403
00:33:41,232 --> 00:33:42,661
Mere puppets.

404
00:33:42,800 --> 00:33:45,997
You need to see them living,
the way they caught his eye.

405
00:33:46,320 --> 00:33:47,465
That's impossible.

406
00:33:47,567 --> 00:33:49,226
Almost. Not quite.

407
00:33:50,864 --> 00:33:52,871
What were the yards like?

408
00:33:53,872 --> 00:33:57,734
Big backyards, fenced,
some hedges. Why?

409
00:33:58,160 --> 00:33:59,589
Because if this pilgrim...

410
00:33:59,664 --> 00:34:01,671
feels a special relationship
with the moon...

411
00:34:01,744 --> 00:34:04,427
he might like to go outside and look at it.

412
00:34:04,528 --> 00:34:06,350
You ever seen blood in the moonlight?

413
00:34:06,448 --> 00:34:08,303
It appears quite black.

414
00:34:08,527 --> 00:34:11,876
If one were nude, say,
it'd be better to have...

415
00:34:11,952 --> 00:34:13,807
outdoor privacy for that sort of thing.

416
00:34:14,640 --> 00:34:17,324
You think the yards are a factor
when he selects victims?

417
00:34:17,392 --> 00:34:18,374
Yes.

418
00:34:18,800 --> 00:34:22,061
And there will be more of them,
of course. Victims.

419
00:34:23,312 --> 00:34:25,581
You'll be wanting lots
of these little chinwags...

420
00:34:25,680 --> 00:34:27,305
- I take it.
- I might not have time.

421
00:34:27,408 --> 00:34:28,586
I do.

422
00:34:28,784 --> 00:34:30,278
I have oodles.

423
00:34:30,352 --> 00:34:32,294
I need your opinion now.

424
00:34:32,400 --> 00:34:33,993
Then here's one:

425
00:34:34,480 --> 00:34:37,327
You stink of fear
under that cheap lotion.

426
00:34:37,808 --> 00:34:40,939
You stink of fear, Will,
but you're not a coward!

427
00:34:42,480 --> 00:34:44,390
You fear me, but still you came here.

428
00:34:44,463 --> 00:34:47,812
You fear this shy boy,
yet still you seek him out.

429
00:34:50,704 --> 00:34:52,776
Don't you understand, Will?

430
00:34:53,232 --> 00:34:56,101
You caught me
because we're very much alike.

431
00:34:57,680 --> 00:34:59,109
Without our imaginations...

432
00:34:59,184 --> 00:35:01,901
we'd be like all those other
poor dullards.

433
00:35:06,160 --> 00:35:09,095
Fear is the price of our instrument.

434
00:35:09,392 --> 00:35:10,853
But I can help you bear it.

435
00:35:22,384 --> 00:35:23,911
- You getting his face?
- Yeah.

436
00:35:23,984 --> 00:35:25,391
Okay, you got it?

437
00:35:25,808 --> 00:35:27,302
All right,
let's get the fuck out of here.

438
00:35:28,367 --> 00:35:29,578
Sure you're okay?

439
00:35:29,679 --> 00:35:31,174
Yeah, I'm okay.

440
00:35:31,440 --> 00:35:34,157
What do you think he
meant by "see them living"?

441
00:35:34,223 --> 00:35:36,678
I don't know, maybe nothing.

442
00:35:36,784 --> 00:35:39,020
It's hard to separate his bullshit.

443
00:35:39,120 --> 00:35:41,641
But I'm gonna make another pass
at the Leeds' house.

444
00:36:32,240 --> 00:36:33,996
All right, Duchess, doll.
That's it.

445
00:36:34,064 --> 00:36:36,038
Show me what you can do.

446
00:36:37,392 --> 00:36:41,352
Who's that? Get them, Duchess.
Get them, Duch! Go get them!

447
00:36:42,064 --> 00:36:43,755
Go get them, girl!

448
00:36:43,984 --> 00:36:44,878
Okay.

449
00:36:44,944 --> 00:36:46,220
And action!

450
00:36:46,320 --> 00:36:48,142
Charles! What are you doing?

451
00:36:49,040 --> 00:36:49,836
Hey, gang.

452
00:36:49,904 --> 00:36:51,148
You crazy man.

453
00:36:51,248 --> 00:36:53,157
How is everybody doing?

454
00:36:53,232 --> 00:36:54,825
Just home from the store.

455
00:36:54,928 --> 00:36:56,521
- Hi, Daddy.
- That's my girl.

456
00:36:56,592 --> 00:36:58,828
- Hi, Daddy.
- Hi, honey. Billy?

457
00:36:58,928 --> 00:36:59,910
Hi, Dad.

458
00:36:59,984 --> 00:37:01,413
And sweetie?

459
00:37:01,520 --> 00:37:04,553
I am not ready for my close-up,
Mr. DeMille.

460
00:37:04,880 --> 00:37:06,985
What do you think?

461
00:37:07,951 --> 00:37:10,919
Get closer. Get closer.
Little closer.

462
00:37:11,600 --> 00:37:14,185
I think we'd better put
these kids to bed early tonight.

463
00:37:14,288 --> 00:37:16,622
They seem tired. Don't you think?

464
00:37:17,584 --> 00:37:19,755
Here we are at the pool party.

465
00:37:19,823 --> 00:37:21,547
What are you doing? Stop it!

466
00:37:21,647 --> 00:37:23,720
You stop it! I'm telling my mother on you.

467
00:37:23,792 --> 00:37:25,483
Now I get my kiss?

468
00:37:25,552 --> 00:37:29,513
- All right, you want a kiss?
- I want one. The romantic kind.

469
00:37:35,887 --> 00:37:38,189
Jacobi House, Birmingham, Al

470
00:37:44,560 --> 00:37:48,389
Won't nobody get in through here
again. I'll guaran-damn-tee it.

471
00:37:51,503 --> 00:37:54,667
Why didn't he break in
down there? It's more hidden.

472
00:37:54,768 --> 00:37:56,743
Hell, that door's got deadbolts.

473
00:37:56,848 --> 00:37:58,823
Reckon he was in too big a hurry.

474
00:38:00,112 --> 00:38:02,184
No, this one doesn't hurry.

475
00:38:55,664 --> 00:38:57,998
You sat right here, didn't you?

476
00:38:58,192 --> 00:39:00,843
You watched the children bury the cat.

477
00:39:00,912 --> 00:39:03,116
And then you waited for dark.

478
00:39:21,808 --> 00:39:24,557
You're proud.
You had to sign your work.

479
00:39:59,984 --> 00:40:02,439
Grandma? Grandma?

480
00:40:03,472 --> 00:40:04,781
I'm sorry.

481
00:40:04,880 --> 00:40:09,353
I've never seen a child
as dirty and disgusting as you.

482
00:40:09,424 --> 00:40:12,239
Look at you! You're soaking wet.
Get out of my bed.

483
00:40:12,304 --> 00:40:14,508
- No.
- Go back to your room.

484
00:40:14,960 --> 00:40:16,421
You're hurting me!

485
00:40:16,528 --> 00:40:18,699
Shut up, you filthy little beast!

486
00:40:18,800 --> 00:40:21,833
I should have put you in
an orphanage, grandson or not.

487
00:40:21,904 --> 00:40:25,516
Grandma, don't hurt me.

488
00:40:25,807 --> 00:40:26,920
You're hurting me!

489
00:40:26,992 --> 00:40:28,137
Into the bathroom!

490
00:40:28,239 --> 00:40:31,884
Take off your nightshirt,
and wipe yourself off. Hurry up!

491
00:40:33,200 --> 00:40:35,655
Now give me my scissors
from the medicine chest.

492
00:40:35,760 --> 00:40:36,688
Please, no!

493
00:40:36,752 --> 00:40:39,469
Take that filthy thing
in your hand. Stretch it out.

494
00:40:39,568 --> 00:40:40,713
No, Grandma.

495
00:40:40,784 --> 00:40:41,732
- Now!
- Please!

496
00:40:41,840 --> 00:40:44,774
Look down. Do you want
me to cut it off? Do you?

497
00:40:44,880 --> 00:40:46,156
No, Grandma!

498
00:40:46,223 --> 00:40:47,979
I pledge you my word, Francis...

499
00:40:48,080 --> 00:40:49,989
if you ever make
your bed dirty again...

500
00:40:50,063 --> 00:40:51,885
I'll cut it off.
Do you understand?

501
00:40:51,952 --> 00:40:56,076
I'll be a good boy.
I promise.

502
00:42:47,728 --> 00:42:49,419
Good morning, Will.

503
00:42:49,552 --> 00:42:51,789
So nice of you to visit again.

504
00:42:54,288 --> 00:42:56,622
He carved this on a tree
near the Jacobi house.

505
00:42:57,200 --> 00:42:58,541
With a Buck knife.

506
00:42:58,640 --> 00:43:00,615
The same one later used
on Charles Leeds.

507
00:43:00,912 --> 00:43:01,894
Yes.

508
00:43:05,167 --> 00:43:06,956
Take a walk with me.

509
00:43:08,463 --> 00:43:11,311
He had a second tool, too.
A bolt cutter.

510
00:43:11,600 --> 00:43:13,258
He used that to clear his view.

511
00:43:13,359 --> 00:43:14,374
But?

512
00:43:14,608 --> 00:43:16,518
I don't think
that's what he brought it for.

513
00:43:17,392 --> 00:43:19,563
It's too heavy. Too awkward.

514
00:43:19,952 --> 00:43:21,675
And he had to carry it a long way.

515
00:43:21,743 --> 00:43:24,045
And what do we make of that symbol?

516
00:43:24,112 --> 00:43:25,705
Asian Studies at Langley...

517
00:43:25,808 --> 00:43:27,979
identified it as a Chinese character.

518
00:43:28,688 --> 00:43:30,510
It appears on a mah-jong piece.

519
00:43:30,608 --> 00:43:33,641
- It marks the Red Dragon.
- Red Dragon. Correct.

520
00:43:34,127 --> 00:43:36,397
This boy begins to interest me.

521
00:43:36,784 --> 00:43:40,046
We don't know what greater
meaning the symbol might have...

522
00:43:40,112 --> 00:43:42,348
Do you like
my little exercise cage, Will?

523
00:43:42,448 --> 00:43:45,230
My so-called lawyer
is always nagging Dr. Chilton...

524
00:43:45,328 --> 00:43:46,506
for better accommodations.

525
00:43:46,607 --> 00:43:48,549
I don't know
which is the greater fool.

526
00:43:48,623 --> 00:43:50,827
Perhaps if you could offer
some insight into...

527
00:43:50,928 --> 00:43:54,343
"A robin redbreast in a cage
Puts all heaven in a rage"

528
00:43:55,599 --> 00:43:58,861
Ever been a redbreast, Will?
Of course you have.

529
00:43:59,791 --> 00:44:02,060
I'm allowed 30 minutes in here,
once a week.

530
00:44:02,160 --> 00:44:03,884
Get to the point.

531
00:44:04,304 --> 00:44:06,857
He meant to use the bolt cutter
to enter the house...

532
00:44:06,960 --> 00:44:07,975
but he didn't.

533
00:44:08,079 --> 00:44:10,600
Instead he broke in
through the patio doors.

534
00:44:11,120 --> 00:44:13,902
The noise woke Jacobi, and he
had to shoot him on the stairs.

535
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:15,887
That wasn't planned.
It was sloppy.

536
00:44:15,952 --> 00:44:17,741
And that's not like him.

537
00:44:18,383 --> 00:44:20,772
We mustn't judge too harshly, Will.

538
00:44:20,880 --> 00:44:22,124
It was his first time.

539
00:44:23,248 --> 00:44:26,117
Have you never felt
a sudden rush of panic?

540
00:44:31,344 --> 00:44:33,995
Yeah, that's the fear we talked about.

541
00:44:34,064 --> 00:44:36,519
It takes experience to master it.

542
00:44:36,783 --> 00:44:38,278
You sensed who I was...

543
00:44:38,352 --> 00:44:40,718
back when I was committing
what you call my "crimes."

544
00:44:40,784 --> 00:44:41,798
Yes.

545
00:44:41,872 --> 00:44:44,141
So you were hurt not by a fault
in your perception...

546
00:44:44,240 --> 00:44:45,255
or your instincts...

547
00:44:45,360 --> 00:44:49,102
but because you failed to act
on them until it was too late.

548
00:44:49,744 --> 00:44:52,232
- You could say that.
- But you're wiser now.

549
00:44:52,560 --> 00:44:56,389
Imagine what you would do, Will,
if you could go back in time.

550
00:44:57,104 --> 00:45:00,519
Put two in your head before
you could palm that stiletto.

551
00:45:00,592 --> 00:45:02,185
Very good, Will.

552
00:45:02,543 --> 00:45:05,325
You know,
I believe we're making progress.

553
00:45:05,392 --> 00:45:07,759
And that's what our pilgrim is doing.

554
00:45:07,824 --> 00:45:09,646
He is refining his methods.

555
00:45:09,712 --> 00:45:11,239
He is evolving.

556
00:45:14,288 --> 00:45:17,549
The case file mentioned videos
of the Leeds family.

557
00:45:17,872 --> 00:45:19,398
- I'd like to see those.
- No.

558
00:45:19,471 --> 00:45:21,708
- Why not?
- It would be obscene.

559
00:45:22,032 --> 00:45:25,676
You don't make it easy, do you?
Still, one aims to please.

560
00:45:26,384 --> 00:45:28,457
I'll call you
if I think of anything else.

561
00:45:28,560 --> 00:45:31,081
Would you perhaps like
to leave me your home number?

562
00:45:34,960 --> 00:45:38,156
- That's the end of our session.
- For now.

563
00:45:38,352 --> 00:45:40,424
It was only his first time.

564
00:45:40,624 --> 00:45:43,275
Already in Atlanta he did much better.

565
00:45:43,632 --> 00:45:45,868
Rest assured, my dear Will...

566
00:45:45,968 --> 00:45:48,073
this one will give you
plenty of exercise.

567
00:45:52,240 --> 00:45:54,542
My love to Molly and Josh, goodbye.

568
00:45:54,639 --> 00:45:57,487
Go to the back of the cell,
Dr. Lecter. Face the wall.

569
00:46:00,912 --> 00:46:03,181
If you turn around
before the lock snaps...

570
00:46:03,279 --> 00:46:04,294
you'll get a dart.

571
00:46:04,400 --> 00:46:06,222
- Understood?
- Yes.

572
00:46:06,288 --> 00:46:09,157
You got ten minutes
to talk to your lawyer.

573
00:46:15,632 --> 00:46:18,283
- Starting now.
- Thanks so much, Barney.

574
00:46:23,952 --> 00:46:25,642
Hello, Dr. Lecter?

575
00:46:25,872 --> 00:46:28,686
I have those documents
you requested me...

576
00:46:36,048 --> 00:46:39,114
"Robes, Robespierre, Robin.

577
00:46:39,184 --> 00:46:42,151
"Robin, call for....
Robin, fainting....

578
00:46:43,087 --> 00:46:46,316
"Redbreast in a cage." 406.9.

579
00:46:51,248 --> 00:46:54,030
"A robin redbreast in a cage
Puts all heaven in a rage"

580
00:46:54,128 --> 00:46:55,175
Yes, that's it.

581
00:46:55,280 --> 00:46:57,352
William Blake.
Auguries of Innocence.

582
00:46:57,424 --> 00:46:58,504
Think you got it?

583
00:46:58,607 --> 00:46:59,917
Yeah, we should have.

584
00:46:59,984 --> 00:47:02,602
We have some books
of Blake's paintings, too.

585
00:47:02,799 --> 00:47:05,101
- Want to see them?
- Yeah. Thanks.

586
00:47:05,488 --> 00:47:06,949
Psychology Department...

587
00:47:07,024 --> 00:47:08,682
University of Chicago.
Dr. Bloom's office.

588
00:47:08,752 --> 00:47:11,654
Hi. This is Bob Greer at Blaine
and Edwards Publishing.

589
00:47:11,760 --> 00:47:14,858
Dr. Bloom asked me to send
The Psychiatrist and the Law...

590
00:47:14,960 --> 00:47:15,942
to Will Graham.

591
00:47:16,048 --> 00:47:18,437
His assistant was
supposed to give me...

592
00:47:18,511 --> 00:47:21,381
the address and phone number,
but, darn it, she never did.

593
00:47:21,487 --> 00:47:24,138
I'm just a temp.
Linda will be in on Monday.

594
00:47:24,240 --> 00:47:26,825
I have to catch FedEx
in about five minutes.

595
00:47:26,928 --> 00:47:28,357
I hate to bother Dr. Bloom
about it...

596
00:47:28,432 --> 00:47:30,188
because he told Linda to send it...

597
00:47:30,287 --> 00:47:32,262
and I don't want
to get her into trouble.

598
00:47:32,368 --> 00:47:35,018
It's right there in the Rolodex,
or whatever.

599
00:47:35,120 --> 00:47:37,837
I'll dance at your wedding
if you read it to me.

600
00:47:37,904 --> 00:47:40,719
I don't know.
I'm really not supposed to.

601
00:47:40,784 --> 00:47:42,988
Be a darling and flip
that old rascal...

602
00:47:43,088 --> 00:47:44,746
I won't take up any more of your time.

603
00:47:44,848 --> 00:47:46,953
Graham, Will.

604
00:47:47,984 --> 00:47:49,991
All right. Just a minute.

605
00:47:51,792 --> 00:47:54,126
"Gibson, Gordon, Graham."

606
00:47:54,192 --> 00:47:55,620
It doesn't give a home address.

607
00:47:55,728 --> 00:47:57,037
What does it have, dear?

608
00:47:57,104 --> 00:48:01,512
"FBI, 935 Pennsylvania Avenue
Northwest, Washington, D.C."

609
00:48:01,584 --> 00:48:03,406
- Yeah?
- And let's see.

610
00:48:04,368 --> 00:48:05,677
Here it is.

611
00:48:05,807 --> 00:48:09,550
"P.O. Box 3680,
Marathon, Florida."

612
00:48:09,712 --> 00:48:11,238
- Marathon.
- Yes.

613
00:48:12,208 --> 00:48:14,794
That's fine. You're an angel.

614
00:49:06,800 --> 00:49:08,622
I'm Francis Dolarhyde.

615
00:49:09,200 --> 00:49:11,655
I've come for the package of infrared.

616
00:49:11,760 --> 00:49:14,662
Right. Put your back
against the door and come...

617
00:49:14,960 --> 00:49:17,710
forward three steps till
you feel tile under your feet.

618
00:49:17,807 --> 00:49:20,044
And there's a stool just on the left.

619
00:49:22,128 --> 00:49:25,543
Same Mr. D who's head
of Tech Services, am I right?

620
00:49:26,512 --> 00:49:28,137
I'm Reba McClane.

621
00:49:28,784 --> 00:49:31,948
Just a second more
and I will get you some light.

622
00:49:34,640 --> 00:49:36,712
Okay, here we go.

623
00:49:41,103 --> 00:49:43,438
So, what do you need the IR for?

624
00:49:44,560 --> 00:49:46,185
It's for the zoo.

625
00:49:46,351 --> 00:49:49,002
They want to photograph
the nocturnal animals.

626
00:49:49,072 --> 00:49:53,327
That's great. I love animals.
I got to warn you, though.

627
00:49:53,583 --> 00:49:57,991
This stuff is pretty sensitive.
It can be mean to handle.

628
00:50:00,528 --> 00:50:03,343
But I guess
I don't need to tell you that.

629
00:50:11,024 --> 00:50:14,439
Hey, Reba. Oh, Mr. D.
Whoa!

630
00:50:15,120 --> 00:50:17,487
I'm not interrupting anything, am I?

631
00:50:17,552 --> 00:50:18,664
No, Ralph.

632
00:50:18,991 --> 00:50:21,031
It's starting to spritz outside.

633
00:50:21,104 --> 00:50:22,119
I'll give you a lift home?

634
00:50:22,192 --> 00:50:23,752
You ride a motorcycle.

635
00:50:23,824 --> 00:50:25,963
How's that gonna help me
with the rain?

636
00:50:26,032 --> 00:50:28,585
I thought maybe
we'd stop off someplace...

637
00:50:28,720 --> 00:50:30,629
have ourselves a little sundowner.

638
00:50:30,704 --> 00:50:33,421
- I've already got a ride.
- It's cool.

639
00:50:33,903 --> 00:50:37,199
That's cool. No problemo.

640
00:50:45,967 --> 00:50:49,579
If there's anything I hate worse
than pity, it's fake pity.

641
00:50:49,680 --> 00:50:52,941
Especially from a walking
hard-on like Ralph Mandy.

642
00:50:53,968 --> 00:50:57,034
- Sorry.
- I have no pity.

643
00:51:29,904 --> 00:51:31,333
Ride with me!

644
00:51:32,207 --> 00:51:34,957
Thanks, but I take the bus
all the time.

645
00:51:36,847 --> 00:51:39,815
Mandy is a fool. Ride with me...

646
00:51:42,255 --> 00:51:43,848
for my pleasure.

647
00:51:57,263 --> 00:52:00,045
You want to come in?
I'll fix us a drink.

648
00:52:06,159 --> 00:52:09,356
- Maybe another time.
- I will come in.

649
00:52:17,264 --> 00:52:19,206
When is the zoo project?

650
00:52:19,855 --> 00:52:23,685
- Maybe next week. They'll call.
- I love zoos.

651
00:52:25,424 --> 00:52:29,580
In fact one of my earliest
memories is seeing a cougar...

652
00:52:30,128 --> 00:52:31,983
when I was about five.

653
00:52:32,079 --> 00:52:35,014
I didn't lose my sight
till I was seven. Diphtheria.

654
00:52:35,088 --> 00:52:37,292
Could you hand me that knife?

655
00:52:53,488 --> 00:52:57,743
I've always tried to hang on
to what that cougar looked like.

656
00:52:58,703 --> 00:53:02,478
But by now, to tell the truth,
what I see in my head...

657
00:53:02,576 --> 00:53:04,616
is probably not in the least bit
like a cougar.

658
00:53:04,688 --> 00:53:06,760
It's more like a donkey or a goat.

659
00:53:06,864 --> 00:53:09,515
You know, sometimes I'm not
so sure I really saw him.

660
00:53:09,615 --> 00:53:12,299
Maybe he's just
something I dreamed up.

661
00:53:15,440 --> 00:53:16,716
You okay?

662
00:53:18,960 --> 00:53:21,033
You don't say much, do you?

663
00:53:21,456 --> 00:53:23,049
No, I guess not.

664
00:53:25,904 --> 00:53:30,311
Let's talk about something
and get it out of the way, okay?

665
00:53:39,727 --> 00:53:41,931
I can hear that you've had...

666
00:53:42,928 --> 00:53:45,262
some kind of soft palate repair.

667
00:53:46,320 --> 00:53:49,800
But I understand you fine
because you speak very well.

668
00:53:50,768 --> 00:53:53,768
If you don't want to talk to me,
that's cool.

669
00:53:54,800 --> 00:53:57,320
But I hope that you will, because...

670
00:53:58,608 --> 00:54:00,550
I know what it's like
to have people...

671
00:54:00,655 --> 00:54:03,176
always thinking that you're different.

672
00:54:06,640 --> 00:54:08,047
That's good.

673
00:54:10,896 --> 00:54:12,718
May I touch your face?

674
00:54:13,968 --> 00:54:16,837
I want to know
if you're smiling or frowning.

675
00:54:16,944 --> 00:54:20,239
I want to know whether I should
just shut up or not.

676
00:54:30,384 --> 00:54:32,620
Take my word that I'm smiling.

677
00:54:36,623 --> 00:54:38,052
I have to go.

678
00:54:38,160 --> 00:54:40,200
If I offended you, I didn't mean to.

679
00:54:40,496 --> 00:54:41,423
No.

680
00:54:48,495 --> 00:54:50,535
F.B.I. Headquarters,
Washington, D.C.

681
00:54:50,608 --> 00:54:52,430
I don't know what they were like.

682
00:54:52,495 --> 00:54:55,048
It'd help if I could see
some of their personal effects.

683
00:54:55,119 --> 00:54:57,803
Diaries, letters.
Do you have those things?

684
00:54:57,903 --> 00:54:59,878
I sure do. I mean, other than...

685
00:54:59,984 --> 00:55:02,439
one or two little keepsakes
Niles Jacobi got.

686
00:55:03,855 --> 00:55:06,921
That would be Mr. Jacobi's
surviving son by his first wife?

687
00:55:07,024 --> 00:55:10,220
Yes. As their executor, I keep
all that stuff in the office...

688
00:55:10,288 --> 00:55:14,084
along with some of the smaller
valuables, till after probate.

689
00:55:14,223 --> 00:55:16,940
But the Birmingham P.D.'s
been all through it.

690
00:55:17,008 --> 00:55:19,495
Could you pack those things
and ship them up to me?

691
00:55:23,407 --> 00:55:26,407
I hate to ask.
I know it's a pain in the ass.

692
00:55:28,815 --> 00:55:29,993
Hell...

693
00:55:30,768 --> 00:55:33,768
probate judge is
an old golfing buddy of mine.

694
00:55:35,120 --> 00:55:39,593
Son, just tell me you're
gonna nail that son of a bitch.

695
00:55:39,760 --> 00:55:41,007
We're doing our best.

696
00:55:42,128 --> 00:55:44,168
Hey, thanks, Mr. Metcalf.

697
00:55:44,240 --> 00:55:47,109
A note hidden in Lecter's cell.
Sounds like a fan letter.

698
00:55:47,215 --> 00:55:48,841
Might've been mailed
by the Tooth Fairy.

699
00:55:48,944 --> 00:55:50,405
He wants Lecter's approval.

700
00:55:50,480 --> 00:55:52,684
He's curious about you.
He's asking questions.

701
00:55:52,784 --> 00:55:54,442
I've scrambled a chopper.

702
00:55:54,543 --> 00:55:55,820
Does Lecter know we have the note?

703
00:55:55,888 --> 00:55:58,157
Not yet. It was found in
a routine cleanup.

704
00:55:58,256 --> 00:55:59,598
They don't open his mail?

705
00:55:59,695 --> 00:56:01,288
Need a warrant.
X-rays only.

706
00:56:01,359 --> 00:56:03,399
- Where's Lecter?
- The holding cage.

707
00:56:03,504 --> 00:56:04,878
Can he see his cell?

708
00:56:04,976 --> 00:56:07,365
No. But he's been there
almost half an hour.

709
00:56:07,440 --> 00:56:09,000
He'll soon start to wonder
what's wrong.

710
00:56:09,104 --> 00:56:11,078
We got to buy time, Jack.

711
00:56:14,064 --> 00:56:15,438
- Dr. Chilton.
- Yes?

712
00:56:15,536 --> 00:56:17,096
Call your building superintendent...

713
00:56:17,167 --> 00:56:18,596
or engineer, whoever's in charge.

714
00:56:18,704 --> 00:56:21,421
Tell him to pull the circuit
breakers on Lecter's hall.

715
00:56:21,488 --> 00:56:24,390
Have the super walk down
the hall past the cell...

716
00:56:24,495 --> 00:56:25,444
carrying tools.

717
00:56:25,520 --> 00:56:29,742
He'll be in a hurry, pissed off,
too busy to answer questions.

718
00:56:29,807 --> 00:56:32,873
Don't touch the note, okay?

719
00:56:33,424 --> 00:56:35,180
Graham's on his way.

720
00:56:35,504 --> 00:56:39,050
Listen up! We've got a note
coming in on the fly...

721
00:56:39,151 --> 00:56:43,013
possibly from the Tooth Fairy.
Number One Priority.

722
00:56:43,472 --> 00:56:45,893
It has to go back to
Lecter's cell within the hour...

723
00:56:45,967 --> 00:56:47,244
unmarked.

724
00:56:47,568 --> 00:56:51,692
We'll need Hair and Fiber,
Latent Prints, then Documents.

725
00:56:52,176 --> 00:56:55,210
I'll walk it through myself.
Let's go, people!

726
00:56:58,672 --> 00:57:01,541
My dear Dr. Lecter.
I wanted to tell you...

727
00:57:01,616 --> 00:57:02,564
I'm delighted...

728
00:57:02,640 --> 00:57:04,615
that you've taken an interest in me.

729
00:57:04,688 --> 00:57:08,812
And when I learned of your vast
correspondence, I thought:

730
00:57:09,423 --> 00:57:12,107
"Dare I?" Of course I do.

731
00:57:14,096 --> 00:57:16,365
I don't believe
you'll tell them who I am.

732
00:57:16,464 --> 00:57:20,042
Besides, what particular body
I currently occupy is trivial.

733
00:57:20,144 --> 00:57:23,013
The important thing is
what I am becoming.

734
00:57:23,504 --> 00:57:27,148
I know that you alone can
understand this transformation.

735
00:57:27,568 --> 00:57:30,382
I have some things
I'd love to show you.

736
00:57:30,543 --> 00:57:33,860
If circumstances permit,
I hope we can correspond.

737
00:57:34,896 --> 00:57:36,805
I have admired you for years
and have...

738
00:57:36,912 --> 00:57:39,083
a complete collection
of your press notices.

739
00:57:39,183 --> 00:57:42,118
Actually, I think of them
as unfair reviews.

740
00:57:42,863 --> 00:57:44,587
As unfair as mine.

741
00:57:45,295 --> 00:57:48,776
They do like to sling demeaning
nicknames, don't they?

742
00:57:49,072 --> 00:57:52,421
"The Tooth Fairy." What could be
more inappropriate?

743
00:57:52,848 --> 00:57:55,815
It would shame me for you to
read that, if I didn't know...

744
00:57:55,888 --> 00:57:58,539
you had suffered the same
distortions in the press.

745
00:57:58,608 --> 00:58:01,128
I'm fed up with this
bloody stupid building!

746
00:58:01,232 --> 00:58:02,541
Every day something breaking.

747
