1001
01:14:18,800 --> 01:14:20,872
That's all, Mr. Lounds.

1002
01:14:20,944 --> 01:14:22,635
You did very well.

1003
01:14:22,864 --> 01:14:24,773
Will you let me go now?

1004
01:14:24,976 --> 01:14:26,088
Soon.

1005
01:14:26,415 --> 01:14:30,060
There's one more way I can
help you to better understand.

1006
01:14:30,352 --> 01:14:32,327
I want to understand.

1007
01:14:32,976 --> 01:14:35,594
I do.
And I'm really gonna be fair...

1008
01:14:36,112 --> 01:14:37,541
from now on.

1009
01:14:38,864 --> 01:14:40,325
You know that.

1010
01:14:46,831 --> 01:14:47,976
Hello?

1011
01:14:48,880 --> 01:14:50,822
Oh, God, no!

1012
01:15:18,192 --> 01:15:20,396
I have had a great privilege.

1013
01:15:20,783 --> 01:15:22,693
I have seen with...

1014
01:15:22,800 --> 01:15:27,307
wonder and awe the strength
of the Great Red Dragon.

1015
01:15:28,048 --> 01:15:31,277
He has helped me to understand
his splendor...

1016
01:15:31,343 --> 01:15:33,515
and now I want to serve him.

1017
01:15:35,280 --> 01:15:37,898
He knows you made me lie, Will Graham.

1018
01:15:38,767 --> 01:15:40,677
Because I was forced to lie...

1019
01:15:40,752 --> 01:15:43,654
he will be more merciful to me
than to you.

1020
01:15:46,992 --> 01:15:48,137
Hello?

1021
01:15:48,879 --> 01:15:50,821
Oh, God, no!

1022
01:16:12,592 --> 01:16:15,177
We can let this tie us up in knots...

1023
01:16:15,344 --> 01:16:17,351
or we can learn from it.

1024
01:16:18,448 --> 01:16:21,066
Maybe even use it
to catch the bastard.

1025
01:16:26,608 --> 01:16:29,030
He had to have a van or panel truck...

1026
01:16:29,103 --> 01:16:31,722
to move Lounds around
in that big old wheelchair.

1027
01:16:32,112 --> 01:16:33,039
Go on.

1028
01:16:33,104 --> 01:16:34,860
He had to already have
the wheelchair...

1029
01:16:34,959 --> 01:16:36,421
or know where to get one fast.

1030
01:16:36,527 --> 01:16:39,113
It's an antique, not something
you'd find in the house.

1031
01:16:39,184 --> 01:16:42,697
Does it strike anybody
that he set this up in a hurry?

1032
01:16:42,800 --> 01:16:45,101
The Tattler comes off the press
Monday night.

1033
01:16:45,200 --> 01:16:48,549
By Tuesday morning he's
in Chicago, snatching Lounds.

1034
01:16:48,624 --> 01:16:50,511
He either lives in the Chicago area...

1035
01:16:50,608 --> 01:16:52,942
or he's within a driving radius of...

1036
01:16:53,040 --> 01:16:54,382
call it six hours.

1037
01:16:54,863 --> 01:16:57,416
Find out in this area where
the Tattler was available...

1038
01:16:57,520 --> 01:16:59,429
for early distribution Monday night.

1039
01:16:59,504 --> 01:17:01,260
Start with airports,
all-night newsstands.

1040
01:17:01,360 --> 01:17:03,335
Maybe a newsie
remembers an odd customer.

1041
01:17:03,440 --> 01:17:05,415
Lloyd, this cassette,
enhance the audio.

1042
01:17:05,520 --> 01:17:08,138
Maybe you can pick up
something in the background.

1043
01:17:08,240 --> 01:17:09,418
That wheelchair...

1044
01:17:09,519 --> 01:17:11,494
I want the maker, date,
possible sources.

1045
01:17:11,600 --> 01:17:15,178
Graham and I will coordinate
from Chicago. Let's hustle.

1046
01:17:26,799 --> 01:17:30,345
Look, there's not gonna be
any answers in Chicago, Jack.

1047
01:17:30,991 --> 01:17:33,893
Okay? I mean, Lounds, that was a bonus.

1048
01:17:34,608 --> 01:17:38,798
That was a chance to show off.
It doesn't even fit his pattern.

1049
01:17:39,727 --> 01:17:42,597
The Leeds and the Jacobis
are what he needs.

1050
01:17:49,327 --> 01:17:51,237
I think I should go back to Baltimore.

1051
01:17:51,312 --> 01:17:52,773
After what he tried to pull?

1052
01:17:52,880 --> 01:17:56,109
Lecter picked up on something
in the missing part of the note.

1053
01:17:56,207 --> 01:17:58,663
Not a name, but something,
enough to narrow the search.

1054
01:17:58,768 --> 01:18:00,459
Even if he did, he won't tell you.

1055
01:18:00,560 --> 01:18:02,316
Not unless I can offer him something.

1056
01:18:03,312 --> 01:18:05,003
Congratulations.

1057
01:18:05,072 --> 01:18:09,644
That was most artistic, the way
you disposed of Mr. Lounds.

1058
01:18:10,192 --> 01:18:12,297
Your cell looks bigger
with no books in it.

1059
01:18:12,400 --> 01:18:13,327
Does it?

1060
01:18:13,392 --> 01:18:14,952
I hadn't noticed.

1061
01:18:15,024 --> 01:18:16,300
Oh, you will.

1062
01:18:16,400 --> 01:18:18,309
I have other resources.

1063
01:18:19,632 --> 01:18:21,966
Tell me, Will. Did you enjoy it?

1064
01:18:22,927 --> 01:18:24,618
Your first murder?

1065
01:18:24,784 --> 01:18:27,086
Of course you did.
Why shouldn't it feel good?

1066
01:18:27,152 --> 01:18:28,679
It does to God.

1067
01:18:29,551 --> 01:18:32,617
Why, only last week in Texas,
he dropped a church roof...

1068
01:18:32,720 --> 01:18:34,924
on the heads of 34 of his worshippers...

1069
01:18:34,992 --> 01:18:37,097
as they were groveling through a hymn.

1070
01:18:37,200 --> 01:18:39,949
He wouldn't begrudge you
one journalist.

1071
01:18:40,207 --> 01:18:41,701
Put me next to him, Doctor.

1072
01:18:41,808 --> 01:18:43,335
You and some SWAT team?

1073
01:18:43,440 --> 01:18:45,895
Oh, Will.
Where's the fun in that?

1074
01:18:46,127 --> 01:18:48,615
He'll have to take his chances, too.

1075
01:18:48,784 --> 01:18:50,856
A roof can fall on anybody.

1076
01:18:52,304 --> 01:18:54,638
But not on Molly and Josh, I take it.

1077
01:18:54,704 --> 01:18:56,297
Not yet, anyway.

1078
01:18:56,943 --> 01:18:59,758
First he kills the pet,
then the family.

1079
01:19:00,623 --> 01:19:02,379
Freddy was your pet.

1080
01:19:02,799 --> 01:19:04,360
They're safe now.

1081
01:19:04,432 --> 01:19:06,668
No one will ever be safe
around you, Will.

1082
01:19:16,720 --> 01:19:19,175
Clever work on his note, by the way.

1083
01:19:19,280 --> 01:19:22,313
And that blackout was
an especially nice touch.

1084
01:19:23,440 --> 01:19:25,895
What else was in that note, Doctor?

1085
01:19:29,808 --> 01:19:31,499
Put me next to him!

1086
01:19:31,984 --> 01:19:33,642
That's what you want, isn't it?

1087
01:19:33,712 --> 01:19:35,403
To help him succeed where you failed?

1088
01:19:35,472 --> 01:19:36,617
Twice?

1089
01:19:37,040 --> 01:19:39,244
Give him a chance to kill me.

1090
01:19:40,304 --> 01:19:41,678
Go on, then.

1091
01:19:41,744 --> 01:19:43,817
Seduce me with your wares.

1092
01:19:44,144 --> 01:19:46,445
Full restoration of your privileges.

1093
01:19:46,512 --> 01:19:49,261
Plus computer access
to the AMA archives.

1094
01:19:49,360 --> 01:19:51,913
One hour a week
under supervision, of course...

1095
01:19:51,984 --> 01:19:53,161
but it's a one-time offer.

1096
01:19:53,232 --> 01:19:55,566
It expires
the minute I walk out of here.

1097
01:19:55,632 --> 01:19:57,192
Bit measly, don't you think?

1098
01:19:57,263 --> 01:20:01,224
Turn it down, then. See what
terms you get from Chilton.

1099
01:20:01,488 --> 01:20:02,949
Are these threats, William?

1100
01:20:03,023 --> 01:20:06,853
I'm waiting, Doctor. Or maybe
you've got nothing left to sell.

1101
01:20:10,640 --> 01:20:13,390
A little sample, then. Why not?

1102
01:20:14,224 --> 01:20:16,111
- Seen the Blake, have you?
- Yes.

1103
01:20:16,207 --> 01:20:18,117
No, you've looked but not seen.

1104
01:20:18,192 --> 01:20:20,046
Transformation is the key.

1105
01:20:20,112 --> 01:20:21,900
The man-dragon...

1106
01:20:22,000 --> 01:20:24,455
his ugliness transformed by power.

1107
01:20:24,751 --> 01:20:27,653
Look for a military record
with combat training.

1108
01:20:27,760 --> 01:20:29,735
Look for extensive tattooing...

1109
01:20:29,840 --> 01:20:31,979
and corrective surgery,
most likely to the face.

1110
01:20:32,079 --> 01:20:35,428
Come on, I'm past that already
and you know it.

1111
01:20:35,792 --> 01:20:37,101
Give me what I need.

1112
01:20:37,200 --> 01:20:38,694
How is he choosing the women?

1113
01:20:38,799 --> 01:20:41,701
I've already suggested how.
The answer was in front of you.

1114
01:20:41,808 --> 01:20:44,874
- You looked but didn't see.
- Bullshit! No riddles!

1115
01:20:45,007 --> 01:20:46,152
Just tell me.

1116
01:20:46,223 --> 01:20:47,172
No!

1117
01:20:47,280 --> 01:20:48,295
It's your turn.

1118
01:20:48,368 --> 01:20:50,604
I asked you before
for a small courtesy...

1119
01:20:50,671 --> 01:20:52,679
and you responded rudely.

1120
01:20:53,968 --> 01:20:55,626
Before I tell you anything more...

1121
01:20:55,727 --> 01:20:58,629
you will make
certain arrangements for me.

1122
01:20:58,928 --> 01:21:00,837
What kind of arrangements?

1123
01:21:00,912 --> 01:21:02,538
Oh, nothing much.

1124
01:21:03,312 --> 01:21:05,581
Shall we say dinner and a show?

1125
01:21:08,911 --> 01:21:11,977
You ready to tell me
what kind of outing this is?

1126
01:21:12,847 --> 01:21:13,992
Nope.

1127
01:21:15,152 --> 01:21:18,119
You're just full of surprises,
aren't you, D?

1128
01:21:18,832 --> 01:21:19,944
Yep.

1129
01:21:21,903 --> 01:21:23,594
He's about six feet away.

1130
01:21:23,663 --> 01:21:25,256
Can you smell him?

1131
01:21:25,648 --> 01:21:26,596
Yeah.

1132
01:21:26,672 --> 01:21:30,054
Now, he's a little noisy,
but he's sedated, I assure you.

1133
01:21:30,864 --> 01:21:33,319
Doctor Hassler's about to fix
his broken tooth.

1134
01:21:33,392 --> 01:21:35,017
Glad you could come,
Ms. McClane.

1135
01:21:35,120 --> 01:21:37,640
We appreciate the infrared film,
by the way.

1136
01:21:37,711 --> 01:21:39,238
Two more steps.

1137
01:21:39,792 --> 01:21:42,923
I'll put your left hand
on the edge of the table.

1138
01:21:43,920 --> 01:21:45,808
Now, he's right in front of you.

1139
01:21:45,872 --> 01:21:47,432
Take your time.

1140
01:21:54,512 --> 01:21:56,901
- D?
- I'm here.

1141
01:21:58,927 --> 01:22:00,356
You go ahead.

1142
01:22:43,503 --> 01:22:44,681
Here.

1143
01:22:46,927 --> 01:22:48,869
Why don't you try this?

1144
01:23:33,200 --> 01:23:35,818
Nine steps from the front door
to the clock...

1145
01:23:35,920 --> 01:23:37,643
and three more to this room.

1146
01:23:38,992 --> 01:23:40,846
Sorry. Force of habit.

1147
01:23:46,928 --> 01:23:50,124
That beautiful tiger,
this house, this music....

1148
01:23:50,928 --> 01:23:53,743
I don't think anybody knows you
at all, D.

1149
01:23:53,872 --> 01:23:55,977
Everybody wonders about you, though.

1150
01:23:56,080 --> 01:23:57,868
Especially the women.

1151
01:23:58,608 --> 01:24:00,299
What do they want to know?

1152
01:24:00,399 --> 01:24:01,960
They find you...

1153
01:24:02,032 --> 01:24:04,519
very mysterious and interesting.

1154
01:24:08,464 --> 01:24:10,668
Did they tell you how I look?

1155
01:24:10,959 --> 01:24:14,276
They said that you have
a remarkable body.

1156
01:24:16,080 --> 01:24:20,041
That you're very sensitive about
your face but you shouldn't be.

1157
01:24:20,880 --> 01:24:22,189
Oh, and...

1158
01:24:24,368 --> 01:24:26,277
they asked me if...

1159
01:24:26,960 --> 01:24:29,546
you are as strong as you look.

1160
01:24:30,928 --> 01:24:32,237
And?

1161
01:24:33,616 --> 01:24:35,404
I said I didn't know.

1162
01:25:10,512 --> 01:25:12,584
Where the hell are you, D?

1163
01:25:18,255 --> 01:25:19,717
Here you are.

1164
01:25:24,175 --> 01:25:26,990
Do you want to know
what I think about it?

1165
01:25:48,496 --> 01:25:51,430
Now, would you show me
where the bathroom is?

1166
01:26:23,376 --> 01:26:25,449
I have to do a little work.

1167
01:26:26,480 --> 01:26:29,229
- If I'm keeping you from work...
- No.

1168
01:26:29,328 --> 01:26:31,630
- ...I'll go.
- I want you to be here.

1169
01:26:31,920 --> 01:26:34,604
I do. It's just a tape
I need to watch.

1170
01:26:35,407 --> 01:26:37,131
It won't take long.

1171
01:26:44,815 --> 01:26:47,849
- Do you need to hear it, too?
- No.

1172
01:26:47,952 --> 01:26:49,774
May I keep the music?

1173
01:27:48,975 --> 01:27:50,568
What's it about?

1174
01:27:52,336 --> 01:27:54,572
Some people I'm going to meet.

1175
01:28:04,847 --> 01:28:06,157
So then...

1176
01:28:08,016 --> 01:28:12,424
it's what? It's a corporate promo?
Some kind of homework?

1177
01:28:14,799 --> 01:28:17,865
It's homework. Yeah.

1178
01:28:23,248 --> 01:28:24,971
That's a good idea.

1179
01:28:26,767 --> 01:28:29,156
It's so important to be prepared.

1180
01:28:34,959 --> 01:28:37,807
My God, are you ever!

1181
01:30:08,175 --> 01:30:10,925
No. I won't give her to you. No.

1182
01:30:21,488 --> 01:30:25,165
Please, just for a little while.

1183
01:30:32,496 --> 01:30:34,405
No! You're hurting me!

1184
01:30:55,408 --> 01:30:56,521
No...

1185
01:30:57,712 --> 01:30:59,086
she's nice.

1186
01:31:00,496 --> 01:31:01,837
She's okay.

1187
01:31:45,391 --> 01:31:48,620
I had a really terrific time
last night.

1188
01:31:49,104 --> 01:31:52,300
But this morning you seem
like a different person.

1189
01:31:52,560 --> 01:31:55,178
- Is something wrong?
- I have to go now.

1190
01:31:57,007 --> 01:31:59,080
- I have to go away.
- Where?

1191
01:32:00,143 --> 01:32:01,485
On a trip.

1192
01:32:05,360 --> 01:32:10,313
- When will I see you again?
- Reba, you have to get out. Now.

1193
01:32:14,703 --> 01:32:16,526
Dear Mr. Graham.

1194
01:32:16,719 --> 01:32:20,036
Here are the Jacobis'
personal effects, as discussed.

1195
01:32:20,112 --> 01:32:22,119
I hope these things might help you.

1196
01:32:22,192 --> 01:32:24,363
Good hunting. Byron Metcalf.

1197
01:32:43,312 --> 01:32:45,897
How many more
times are we going to watch this?

1198
01:32:46,000 --> 01:32:49,196
"See them living, " he said,
"right in front of you."

1199
01:32:49,263 --> 01:32:51,238
It's something about
these home movies.

1200
01:32:51,312 --> 01:32:54,029
Lecter keeps saying,
"You looked, but didn't see."

1201
01:32:54,128 --> 01:32:56,266
Lecter says a lot of things.

1202
01:32:58,928 --> 01:33:01,710
Sad damn thing.
But we already knew that.

1203
01:33:02,832 --> 01:33:05,003
We can't afford
to let Lecter waste our...

1204
01:33:05,071 --> 01:33:06,380
No. Again.

1205
01:33:14,608 --> 01:33:17,674
Your dissertation must be
nearly finished, Mr. Crane.

1206
01:33:17,744 --> 01:33:18,693
Nearly.

1207
01:33:18,800 --> 01:33:21,517
It's nice to be able to connect
a face with a name...

1208
01:33:21,584 --> 01:33:23,494
after all our correspondence.

1209
01:33:23,600 --> 01:33:27,429
But, you know, you don't look
like I imagined you looked.

1210
01:33:28,688 --> 01:33:30,662
What did you think I looked like?

1211
01:33:31,343 --> 01:33:32,521
Different.

1212
01:33:43,471 --> 01:33:44,682
Thank you.

1213
01:33:47,120 --> 01:33:49,803
Right there! There.

1214
01:33:50,064 --> 01:33:52,235
That's what he wanted
the bolt cutter for.

1215
01:33:52,304 --> 01:33:55,599
To cut that padlock
and go in through the basement.

1216
01:33:56,207 --> 01:33:58,346
But that's a different door.

1217
01:33:59,152 --> 01:34:02,949
I don't get it. The one I saw
was flush steel with deadbolts.

1218
01:34:03,952 --> 01:34:07,661
Jacobi had a new door installed.
Beginning of January, I think.

1219
01:34:07,760 --> 01:34:09,189
It's in here somewhere.

1220
01:34:09,968 --> 01:34:12,717
Think he cased the house
with the old door?

1221
01:34:12,783 --> 01:34:14,474
He brought the bolt cutter, didn't he?

1222
01:34:14,543 --> 01:34:15,852
He was sure he'd need it.

1223
01:34:15,920 --> 01:34:18,375
Why case it two months
in advance and not check it?

1224
01:34:18,480 --> 01:34:20,782
I don't know. He was ready
with the bolt cutter...

1225
01:34:20,880 --> 01:34:22,221
like at the Leeds' house.

1226
01:34:22,320 --> 01:34:23,881
There he was ready
with a glass cutter.

1227
01:34:23,952 --> 01:34:27,334
He must've seen the glass when
he walked in the neighborhood.

1228
01:34:27,440 --> 01:34:29,512
No. You can't see
that door from the yard.

1229
01:34:29,584 --> 01:34:32,137
There's a porch lattice in the way.

1230
01:34:33,232 --> 01:34:35,916
Jack, he knew
the inside of the houses.

1231
01:34:47,600 --> 01:34:49,388
Remarkable, isn't it?

1232
01:34:50,608 --> 01:34:52,430
Two hundred years old.

1233
01:34:54,448 --> 01:34:55,877
Yet so fresh.

1234
01:34:56,783 --> 01:34:58,060
So vivid.

1235
01:35:32,752 --> 01:35:35,174
He almost looks alive, doesn't he?

1236
01:36:20,336 --> 01:36:23,303
We've just gotten
a report here from the....

1237
01:36:34,320 --> 01:36:37,134
Do you still have
the Jacobis' check stubs...

1238
01:36:37,231 --> 01:36:38,508
and credit card statements?

1239
01:36:39,120 --> 01:36:41,421
We're looking for any kind
of service call or purchase...

1240
01:36:41,520 --> 01:36:42,862
that might've required a stranger...

1241
01:36:42,960 --> 01:36:44,236
to enter the house.

1242
01:36:44,303 --> 01:36:47,151
- A repairman, delivery guy.
- Anybody in the house.

1243
01:36:47,216 --> 01:36:48,874
- Yeah.
- We checked.

1244
01:36:48,944 --> 01:36:50,351
I know we checked that...

1245
01:36:50,415 --> 01:36:52,903
but now we got to go back
to before January.

1246
01:36:52,976 --> 01:36:54,798
- Last year's purchase orders.
- Yeah.

1247
01:36:54,863 --> 01:36:57,351
- No collar.
- But please hurry. It's urgent.

1248
01:36:57,424 --> 01:36:58,634
No collar.

1249
01:36:58,703 --> 01:37:00,427
- Metcalf says...
- No collar.

1250
01:37:00,496 --> 01:37:03,343
The dog had no collar
in a neighborhood of dogs...

1251
01:37:03,407 --> 01:37:04,651
but he knew which was theirs.

1252
